Detailed Description

Formal protocol for an object which can contain Starks in a managed object context, and has a Starker available.

Conforming classes will provide methods to

Access the Starker (of course!) Answer questions regarding placing additional Starks in the receiver Identify the class's Browfile (optional)

This protocol was established to express the commonality between the internal representation of Starks in a BmxBk and their external representation in an Extore. BmxBk and Extore adopt this protocol.

Member Function Documentation

- (Browfile*) browfile   [optional]

Gets the receiver's browfile.

This method is optional because Extore subclasses will have a browfile but BmxBk objects will not.

Returns:
The receiver's browfile

- (BkmmHas) hasBar  

Returns whether or not the receiver's ownerApp has a permanent collection called a "Bookmarks Bar", "Bookmarks Toolbar" or equivalent.

Returns:
Returns BkmmHasExplicit If it has an explicit Bookmarks Bar with children not repeated in other collections. Returns BkmmHasSmart if it creates a Bookmarks Bar dynamically by copying items in other collections which have some kind of Bookmarks Bar "flag". Returns BkmmHasNot if receiver's ownerApp has no kind of Bookmarks Bar whatsoever are stored

- (BOOL) hasOhared  

Returns whether or not the receiver's ownerApp has a permanent collection designated for "Shared" bookmarks.

Do not confuse this with the capacity of a web service external store to set individual bookmarks "shared" or "private".

- (Starype) highestAllowedParentTypeRankForItem: (Stark *)  item  

Returns the rank of parent with highest Starype rank that can accept an item as one of its children in the receiver.

Subclasses should override this method

- (void) setToHighestAllowedCollection: (Stark *)  addend
rootCollection: (Stark *)  rootUnderConstruction
barCollection: (Stark *)  barUnderConstruction
menuCollection: (Stark *)  menuUnderConstruction
oharedCollection: (Stark *)  oharedUnderConstruction
unfiledCollection: (Stark *)  unfiledUnderConstruction 

Given a stark which is to be added to the tree of Starks in the receiver's managed object context, and its hypothetical fixture collections sets the stark to the highest-ranking of these collections in which it would be allowed.

The xxxxCollection arguments are required because they are hypothetical. They need not be the actual fixture collections but may be collections who will later contribute their items to their corresponding actual fixture collection.
